06289nam a22007215i 9780822380405DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223804057 a10.1515/97808223804052doi  a(DE-B1597)552203  a(OCoLC)1055303247  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBL65.C8bR457 2001 7aREL0170002bisacsh04a291.1/700aReligions/Globalizations :bTheories and Cases /cDwight N. Hopkins, Lois Ann Lorentzen, David Batstone, Eduardo Mendieta. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One / Theoretical frameworks -- tThe Religion of Globalization -- tThe Sociohistorical Meaning of Liberation Theology (Reflections about Its Origin and World Context) -- tSociety's Religion: The Rise of Social Theory, Globalization, and the Invention of Religion -- tThe Global Rise of Religious Nationalism -- tWho Is an Indian? Religion, Globalization, and Chiapas -- tPart Two / Case studies -- tThe African Transformation of Christianity: Comparative Reflections on Ethnicity and Religious Mobilization in Africa -- tMacroeconomy, Apartheid, & Rituals of Healing in an African Indigenous Church -- t(In)Corporating Threshold Art: Kolam Competitions, Patronage, and Colgate -- tVisa Trouble: Cambodian American Christians and Their Defense of Multiple Citizenships -- tTelevangelism: Local and Global Dimensions -- tDancing to a Different Beat: Emerging Spiritualities in the Network Society -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the majority of cultures around the world, religion permeates and informs everyday rituals of survival and hope. But religion also has served as the foundation for national differences, racial conflicts, class exploitation, and gender discrimination. Indeed, religious spirituality, having been transformed by contemporary economic and political events, remains both empowering and controversial. Religions/Globalizations examines the extent to which globalization and religion are inseparable terms, bound up with each other in a number of critical and mutually revealing ways.As the contributors to this work suggest, a crucial component of globalization-the breakdown of familiar boundaries and power balances-may open a space in which religion can be deployed to help refabricate new communities. Examples of such deployments can be found in the workings of liberation theology in Latin America. In other cases, however, the operations of globalization have provided a space for strident religious nationalism and identity disputes to flourish. Is there in fact a dialectical tension between religion and globalization, a codependence and codeterminism? While religion can be seen as a globalizing force, it has also been transformed and even victimized by globalization.A provocative assessment of a contemporary phenomenon with both cultural and political dimensions, Religions/Globalizations will interest not only scholars in religious studies but also those studying Latin America, the Middle East, South Asia, and Africa.Contributors. David Batstone, Berit Bretthauer, Enrique Dussel, Dwight N. Hopkins, Mark Juergensmeyer, Lois Ann Lorentzen, Eduardo Mendieta, Vijaya Rettakudi Nagarajan, Kathryn Poethig, Lamin Sanneh, Linda E. Thomas  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aGlobalizationxReligious aspects. 0aReligion and culture. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aBatstone, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBretthauer, Berit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 